    {
        "content": "<p>sorry I'm not quite sure what you mean by that: I still can't provide an explicit derivative to <code>DifferentiableAt</code>. Essentially what I want is after calculating an derivative explicitly and I have a statement of the form </p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"n\">hf</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">deriv</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"k\">fun</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x'</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">f</span><span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">x'</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">f'</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>I can use this to show</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"n\">HasDerivAt</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">f</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">f'</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>which is much more useful for <code>fun_prop</code> type arguments. There is <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=HasDerivAt.deriv#doc\">docs#HasDerivAt.deriv</a> in the forward direction but not the reverse direction. My understanding is that the value of <code>deriv</code> defaults to zero when the function is not differentiable, hence it's not an equivalence, but if I'm able to show the derivative explicitly surely it satisfies all the differentiability conditions etc., so I don't see why tactics that simplify <code>deriv</code> shouldn't work on <code>HasDerivAt</code></p>",
        "id": 514178318,
        "sender_full_name": "ZhiKai Pong",
        "timestamp": 1745514105
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You can use <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=DifferentiableAt.hasDerivAt#doc\">docs#DifferentiableAt.hasDerivAt</a> to prove the derivative is given by <code>deriv</code>, and then you can substitute <code>hf</code> with <code>rw</code> or some other method.</p>",
